<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41079d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41079d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41079d"> 79(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> locus penitentiae</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Sir H. Curtis Bennett&mdash;&hellip; There is surely a <mark><i>locus p&oelig;nitenti&aelig;</i></mark> for every one, and if a letter is written and meant to convey that Mrs. Thompson was anxious in April that her husband should die, can it possibly be said to be evidence that she, although present and not striking any blow upon 4th October, was in fact a party, a principal, to the killing of her husband? I submit not. <small> Filson Young, <a name="FYTF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FYTF"><cite title="source">Trial of Frederick Bywaters and Edith Thompson</cite></a> (1923) 5-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
